video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
I found this episode difficult to finish. It took me 2 days. I felt like I was listening to my doctor telling me that my experience could not have happened, again. I continued to listen because I don’t want to fall prey to confirmation bias. I want to understand.

The doctor is pleasant, polite, committed, educated, humble, caring, old enough to have the respect of age and young enough to be extremely attractive. She is convincing and easy to watch — until you listen closely to what she’s saying. Her belief in standard theories of nutrition is… unsettling.

She is genuine. She believes, as do many doctors, standard nutritional advice. However, when I followed this standard advice, I continued to have health issues. These only resolved when I tried some of methods that she refers to as “nutribullocks.” And I am not alone. I am joined my numerous doctors and researchers that have followed, the standard advice, and still developed the health issues that following that advice was supposed to prevent.

Simply put, it’s bad science to decide to ignore anecdotal evidence or case studies. These events happened. If your theory fails to address these exceptions, it cannot be accepted as fact. If statistical or observational analysis haven’t found an issues with your theory — and issues still exist — you don’t have an answer. Absence of evidence cannot provide evidence of absence.

It is either naive or ignorant to suggest that there is no influence from a funding body, even though the funding body is not involved in the actual research. After all, no matter what grant request you write, the funder gets to choose what they will fund or will not fund. That choice leaves many of us in the dark.

As businesses food corporations will approve what they feel is safe for them to approve. Will they continue to fund a researcher that has proven their products to be unsafe? Will they pull or change a ingredients for more expensive options unless they are forced to?

Look at it this way. It’s like a detective [a scientist] being directed where to look [with funding approval] for a body [a toxic effect] by a suspect [food or pharmaceutical corporation].

People are trying to be healthier. The smoking gun is the continuing increases in chronic illnesses that are plaguing us at younger and younger ages under the status quo.

comment_text:
She works for the BRITISH NUTRITION FOUNDATION - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Nutrition_Foundation
The British Nutrition Foundation is a British lobby group mainly funded by the food industry. It has been widely criticised for conflicts of interest, and for downplaying them. It presents itself to journalists, the public, and the government as an independent, impartial, disinterested, and scientifically rigorous; its industry funders also promote this image.

The BNF has opposed many public-health interventions that might harm food-industry profits, often using tobacco-industry techniques, such as creating unwarranted doubt and uncertainty around the scientific evidence.
In 2023, the BNF had an income of £1.5million, with an expenditure of £1.6million. £0.113million were spent on fundraising.

The British Nutrition Foundation (BNF) receives funding from a wide range of food and drink companies, including major players like *Coca-Cola, Nestlé, Mondelēz, PepsiCo, Mars, Danone, Kerry, and Cargill*. This funding structure has raised concerns about potential conflicts of interest, particularly given the BNF's role in shaping nutrition policy and its relationship with the food industry, according to a LinkedIn post. The BNF has been described as a "bridge between government, science, industry, and education" but critics argue that its funding model compromises its impartiality and ability to act independently, according to a LinkedIn post. The foundation's acceptance of funding from companies whose products are linked to diet-related diseases has been highlighted as a particular area of concern.

comment_text:
Outside of natural pressed oils such as olive, coconut, avocado, sesame, there is nothing natural or good about seed oils (cotton seed, canola, soy, corn etc.), these toxic oils are not naturally occurring in the environments and are made via the use of Hexane extraction which is a petroleum derivative. There is no amount of credentials after your name to convince me otherwise. 

Profile of hexane used to make "healthy seed oils": Hexane, particularly n-hexane, is known to cause significant neurotoxicity, primarily affecting the peripheral nervous system. The main toxic effect is degenerative distal axonopathy, which is caused by the metabolite 2,5-hexanedione (2,5-HD) formed during the metabolism of n-hexane in the liver.

Acute exposure to high concentrations of n-hexane can cause immediate symptoms such as lightheadedness, headache, and confusion, potentially progressing to severe central nervous system depression in extreme cases.
 However, chronic exposure is more concerning, as it leads to long-lasting and even permanent nerve damage in the feet, legs, hands, and arms.

In occupational settings, such as shoe factories where n-hexane is used as a solvent, workers may experience symptoms that begin with nonspecific signs like nausea, anorexia, and weight loss, followed by sensory disturbances like paresthesia in the lower extremities.

https://nj.gov/health/eoh/rtkweb/documents/fs/1340.pdf

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
Recent studies, particularly one published on March 7, 2025, in JAMA Internal Medicine, have shed light on the health impacts of butter versus plant-based oils. This large-scale study, conducted by researchers from Mass General Brigham, Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health, and the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard, tracked the dietary habits of over 220,000 U.S. adults—primarily health professionals—across three cohorts (Nurses’ Health Study, Nurses’ Health Study II, and Health Professionals Follow-up Study) for more than 30 years. Participants reported their food intake every four years, allowing researchers to estimate their consumption of butter (including spreads, blends, and cooking use) and plant-based oils (used in frying, sautéing, baking, and dressings).

The findings indicate a clear distinction in health outcomes. Higher butter consumption was associated with a 15% increased risk of total mortality and a notable rise in cancer mortality compared to those who consumed the least butter. In contrast, higher intake of plant-based oils—specifically olive, canola, and soybean oils—was linked to a 16% lower risk of total mortality, as well as reduced deaths from cancer and cardiovascular disease. A substitution analysis further revealed that replacing just 10 grams (less than a tablespoon) of butter daily with an equivalent amount of plant-based oil could lower overall mortality and cancer mortality by 17%, with olive oil showing particular benefits for cardiovascular health.

Experts attribute these differences to the fatty acid profiles: butter is rich in saturated fats, which are tied to higher LDL cholesterol and inflammation, while plant oils like olive, canola, and soybean are high in unsaturated fats (monounsaturated and polyunsaturated), known to improve cholesterol levels and reduce disease risk. The study aligns with broader evidence, such as the Mediterranean diet’s emphasis on olive oil, which is associated with longevity and lower chronic disease rates. However, not all plant oils are equal—palm and coconut oils, high in saturated fats, were not significantly consumed in this study and may not offer the same benefits.

Limitations include the observational nature of the research (no randomized control) and the participant pool, which may not fully represent the general population due to their health-professional background. Self-reported dietary data also introduces potential recall errors, though the study’s long duration and large sample size bolster its credibility. Critics of seed oils (like soybean and canola) on social media, often linked to movements like "Make America Healthy Again," argue they’re harmful due to industrial processing, but this study found no evidence to support that claim for unhydrogenated versions, challenging such narratives.

In summary, as of March 11, 2025, this research suggests that swapping butter for plant-based oils like olive, canola, or soybean could meaningfully improve long-term health outcomes, though moderation remains key, and individual dietary contexts matter. Future studies aim to explore the biological mechanisms behind these effects.

comment_text:
I don’t get all the negative comments. She was just expressing a differentiated view. Seed oils like rape seed oil for cooking or frying is not bad for you, if you don’t eat fried food every day. What else are you going to use for frying? Certainly not cold pressed olive oil.  Sunflower oil also isn’t as harmful as the majority of comments want to convey. There are different oils for different occasions or type of cooking, for ex. hemp seed oil, sesame oil, linseed oil. These are all healthy oils. Everything should be consumed in moderation of course. 
Fiber helps with the peristaltic of your intestines, btw., it’s not just about the nutrients. Furthermore it can prevent colon cancer. 
What she was expressing about the food industry was that all the “bad food” out there is made to meet the customer’s need, opposed to deliberately wanting to destroy the customers health. It’s your choice and solely your responsibility what to buy. And it really doesn’t make you die, if you eat “bad food” now and then. 
Balance is key with almost everything in life. 
If you eat bad stuff al lot of times, but have a normal BMI and for example exercise a lot, drink mainly water, don’t smoke or have Ny other bad habits I don’t think you should concern yourself too much. 
It’s a bit disapponting how extreme, unreflected and biased most comments under this video are and they are certainly not a good reflection of the commentators general knowledge and ability to process information. Not everything is a conspiracy. And science, studies will never be just black and white. Just take the Information and try out what works for you. This lady does not seem to have any bad intentions.

comment_text: Sarry Berry is a Professor who has conducted a very wide range of  Random Controlled Double-blind trials; she is certainly a leader in her field.  Yes she is a member of the Zoe team but that is a positive and Steven covered that relationship at the end of the video.  Because of Zoe, the number of people in any trial is far higher than Big Food would dream of funding.  Although Zoe is related to the food industry it is NOT a food producer per se (except for a formulated natural food supplement which is intended to ensure busy people can ensure that their diet contains essential elements.  I have watched many videos in which she has participated and am convinced of her competence and sincerity.  You should note that she always caveats what she says and puts the currency of her work in perespective.  I tried Zoe memebership for a year and was impressed by the outcome but did not renew my subscription because the logging of food in the app was time-consuming and sometimes frustrating owing to the 'clunkiness' of the app which, in my view, has inadequate technical support to make it a success. Apart from that, I am retired and have no other connection with Zoe. In sum, I believe the Professor Berry is at the highest level of competence and knowledge in her field and am dismayed at the large number of commenters  who preer 'neutrabollocks' in preference to a wealth of knowledge supported by peer-reviewed scientific trials.

Know how your food is processed. It's usually not the food itself that's evil.

comment_text: @@tatjanakane503You’re also not a seed oil eater then - both avocado and olive oils are extracted from the flesh around their seed; they are essentially fruit oils, and can be produced with minimal processing compared to seed oils. While they still begin to oxidise immediately after production, the rate is slower than with seed oils. Both are best used cold, as they are not heat-stable. Another fruit oil, coconut oil, is both heat stable and shelf stable with a low rancidity index. For some people these 3 fruit oils can still be more pro-inflammatory than tallow or lard.

comment_text:
Potential Concerns:
1. **High in Omega-6 Fatty Acids**: Many seed oils are rich in omega-6 fatty acids. While omega-6s are essential fats, excessive consumption relative to omega-3s (found in fish, flaxseeds, and walnuts) may promote inflammation and contribute to chronic diseases when the balance is skewed.

2. **Processing Methods**: Seed oils are often highly refined and processed, which can involve high heat and chemical solvents. This may lead to the formation of harmful compounds or reduce the oil's nutritional value.

3. **Oxidation**: Seed oils are prone to oxidation, especially when heated at high temperatures. Oxidized oils can produce free radicals, which may damage cells and contribute to inflammation and chronic diseases.

4. **Association with Processed Foods**: Seed oils are commonly found in ultra-processed foods, which are linked to poor health outcomes like obesity, heart disease, and diabetes.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
Unfortunately each person's biases get the best of them before watching the whole video and thinking it through. She is quite nuanced, has many good points; but also have some subconscious biases that she might not be quite be aware of.

Starting with the seed oil, I do think that some amount of seed oil is not necessarily bad and can be beneficial because of omega-6 fatty acids. But that likely is not the whole story. I am sure that omega-6 can still be bad on a high enough dose. It may also depend on if the crop of the seed, was grown on a mass scale with pesticide. If it was just cold pressed or had chemical processing like bleaching, etc. Flat out saying that "seeds oils" are beneficial is not quite right. However, I do think that she is right about people going to the other extreme of only using animal fat being just as wrong. In fact, even olive oil at the amount we consume regular oils is still almost as bad; but people just want to believe otherwise. The quantity makes the poison of almost anything. The problem is that people wants to be able to consume at infinitum without consequences but that is not reality.

The other part that she will meet resistance with the people in the comments, is her a little too generic conclusion that there are no bad actors in the food industry or bad nutritional scientists. I know she didn't explicitly say that but her conclusion about it was a little murky and is where commentators will criticize. It is because there have been bad actors in the food industry that purposely pay nutritional scientists to fabricate results that we are now so up and alert when it happens. What is right about her comment is that not everyone in the food industry is necessarily trying control the world and not all nutritional scientist are bad people. And that from her personal experience, everyone is trying to do what they believe is the right thing (except that what they believe is right may happen to be true within some context and wrong in a more general sense). And she is also right about how the government should help fund them and that they should all work together instead of being fractured.

The root of the problem is more deep because people will want to buy the stuff that saves them the most money. And the stuff that are cheapest and the ones with extended shelf life and often least expensive to produce. But the reason these are cheap and have extended shelf life is because the microbes that will make it go bad, cannot consume it. And most of the times (not necessarily always) the stuff that bad for microbes are also bad for us. So, consumers are greedy in not wanting to spend more and want more convenient things. Food producers will just make what the greedy consumers want. It is greed all around at all levels (as Steve allured to). And we should be working together not against each other. We are collectively working against each other without really realizing.

I do agree with her with most of her other more nuanced points. It is not just about the amount of calories, the structure and processing of the food matters. Eating with joy helps us sustain what and how we eat; so utilize it instead of going against it. How we eat it matters. Sleep and exercise matters. The time which we eat our meals matters. Eating within 10-12hrs is better than an inconsistent eating routine. I don't think she means ill the way some people in the comments are jumping into. But I also think that they have spotted some of her subconscious bias she had as the ones I listed above. And at the same time, she does bring a lots of good points.

I leave you lads with one really good quote I learned on the internet:
"Not a single droplet of rain thinks that they are the cause of a flood"

comment_text: the main problem with seed oils is the way they are extracted: cold pressed they retain their nutritional values, but a lot of them are hexane extracted. Hexane is a hydrocarbon extracted from crude oil. In its pure form, hexane is a colorless solvent that evaporates easily and dissolves only slightly in water. It’s incredibly volatile and highly flammable, and its vapors can be explosive. It is the primary solvent used to extract edible and industrial vegetable oils from the world’s top five commodity oilseeds: soybean, canola, sunflower seed, cottonseed, and peanut. While most of it is recovered (although just the thought that it ever even touched oil that we are going to ingest makes me shiver), there are trace amount that stay in the end product. So I believe that the information given in this interview is not complete.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
I enjoyed aspects of this episode, but I was a little skeptical when Dr. Berry said that hydrogenated oil isn't present in foods anymore.  Is this the case in the UK?  Because I'm almost certainly sure that they're in US foods.  They're just used in amounts that are low enough that companies don't have to label amounts in the Nutrition Facts.

Seed oils not being harmful is interesting.  I definitely haven't heard that before.  I am in agreement that there's more to the omega 6 part of the conversation - specifically, that omega 6 and omega 3 need to be in a certain balance for optimal human health - but I'm gonna have to see more evidence since what she said is different than pretty much everything else I've heard.

And as far as the food industry being out to help consumers...that's an interesting statement.  I'm not saying that companies are malicious, per se, but I do believe evidence suggests that they're way more focused on selling their products, unless they've explicitly taken above-and-beyond steps to ensure a certain quality to their foods, even if it negatively affects their bottom line.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
There are numerous scientific studies that have pointed out the dangers of consuming refined seed oils, especially due to their high content of polyunsaturated fats (PUFAs), oxidation, toxic aldehydes, and imbalances in the omega-6/omega-3 fatty acid ratio. Here I summarize some of the main concerns supported by the scientific literature:

1. High Omega-6 content and imbalance with Omega-3

Excessive consumption of omega-6 fatty acids, present in seed oils such as soybean, corn, sunflower, and canola, has been associated with chronic inflammation, cardiovascular disease, and metabolic disorders.

Key study:
➤ Simopoulos, A. P. (2002). "The importance of the ratio of omega-6/omega-3 essential fatty acids." Biomedicine & Pharmacotherapy.
🔎 Concludes that a high omega-6 intake with a low omega-3 intake promotes inflammation and chronic diseases.

 2. Oxidation and production of toxic aldehydes

When seed oils are heated (such as in frying), they generate lipid oxidation products, such as aldehydes, which are highly toxic and carcinogenic.

Key study:
➤ González, M. J., & Gray, J. I. (1984). "Effects of heating on lipid oxidation in foods." Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition.
🔎 Shows that oils rich in PUFAs are rapidly oxidized by heat, generating harmful compounds.

Key study:
➤ de Souza, R. J., et al. (2015). "Intake of saturated and trans unsaturated fatty acids and risk of all cause mortality, cardiovascular disease, and type 2 diabetes." BMJ.
🔎 Shows that refined oils produce compounds that increase cardiovascular risk.

 3. Impact on metabolic diseases

High consumption of seed oils is linked to insulin resistance, obesity, and type 2 diabetes due to their interference with mitochondrial function.

Key study:
➤ Ramsden, C. E., et al. (2013). "Use of dietary linoleic acid for secondary prevention of coronary heart disease and death: evaluation of recovered data from the Sydney Diet Heart Study and updated meta-analysis." BMJ.
🔎 Found that replacing saturated fats with omega-6-rich oils increased cardiovascular mortality.

4. Effects on mitochondrial function

Excess PUFAs in the diet impair the energy efficiency of mitochondria, which can lead to cellular dysfunction and neurodegenerative diseases.

Key study:
➤ Hulbert, A. J. (2005). "Metabolism and longevity: Is there a role for membrane fatty acids?" Integrative and Comparative Biology.
 🔎 Concludes that cell membranes high in PUFAs are more prone to oxidative damage.

📌 Conclusion

Refined seed oils not only promote inflammation and metabolic diseases, but also generate toxic compounds when heated, increasing the risk of cardiovascular disease, cancer, and mitochondrial deterioration. Studies support that it is preferable to opt for more stable fats such as lard, tallow, ghee, or coconut oil instead of soybean, corn, sunflower, and canola oils.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
This woman is not a scientist. A scientist follows the scientific method, the 'evidence' she talks about does not follow the scientific method. The 'evidence' for seed oils being good is epidemiology they give food frequency questionnaires which are full of issues, including things like classing pizza as red meat and the fact I can't remember what I ate for breakfast let alone over the last year,  and then look at health outcomes. That is step one in the scientific method, observe (and they are not observing well).  Step two is hypothesis. and if that is what they did, that would be fine, because step three is test and step four is refine.  They jump straight from step 1 to claiming it's 'evidence' it's not, when tested the majority of observations derived from epidemiology is proven to be wrong, because of things like healthy user bias, because contrary to what they claim they cannot adjust for all the differences between a healthy person and unhealthy person's habits.  There are however a number of large randomized controlled trails that show at best swapping animal fat for seed oils results in no improvement in health but often show a worse outcome such as greater rates of cancer or heart disease in the intervention group. This includes trails conducted in institutions where the food was well controlled so they knew what the participants were eating not just what they reported eating. These are actual scientific trails. I also find it ironic that she criticizes the  people who highlight the correlation between seed oil consumption and worsening health.  The 'evidence' she claims show seed oil is health is all correlation not causation because epidemiology cannot prove causation. Granted if it meets the Bradford Hill criteria we can be more confident in the likelihood of it being causal (smoking and cancer), but I've never seen a nutritional epidemiology study that actually comes anywhere close to meeting those criteria.

She also makes the mistake of assuming that' health markers' equate to health outcomes, eg LDL causes poor health outcome.  Again this idea is derived from epidemiology and isn't sound, we know from large scale randomized trails such as the woman's health initiative that this isn't true. In that extremely large randomized trial, the only statistically significant difference in outcome between those with high LDL and those with low LDL is those who started the study with heart disease and high LDL lived longer.  This persisted for 7 years, so not a case of LDL was lower because they were dying. Funny that after 7 years they stopped reporting on this metric. Not that they ever put this statistically significant result in the abstract, conclusion or results table, only in the narrative. Which in my opinion is scientific fraud, you don't avoid reporting statistically significant results just because you don't like them!  If the assumption that LDL causes heart disease has been shown to be inaccurate in various studies (it may be a factor in it's development but is not causal) then her whole premise around seed oils being healthy because they lower LDL is wrong.  That is why good randomized controlled trails look at health outcomes not health markers, that way you avoid erroneous assumptions. The trials that look at health outcomes not health markers generally show that swapping saturated fat for  Industrial highly processed seed oils at best results in no benefit and at worse results in worse health outcomes.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
The debate around seed oils (such as soybean, canola, sunflower, and corn oil) is highly polarized. Some experts claim they are safe and even beneficial due to their polyunsaturated fat content, while others argue that they contribute to inflammation and metabolic dysfunction.

Mechanistic Explanation of Why Seed Oils Might Be Harmful:

1. High in Omega-6 Fatty Acids and Imbalanced Omega-6/Omega-3 Ratio:
Seed oils contain high levels of linoleic acid (LA), an omega-6 polyunsaturated fat (PUFA).
Historically, humans consumed omega-6 and omega-3 fats in a ratio of approximately 1:1 to 4:1, but modern diets often exceed 20:1 due to widespread seed oil consumption.
Omega-6 fats are precursors to pro-inflammatory eicosanoids (such as prostaglandins and leukotrienes), while omega-3 fats are anti-inflammatory.
A chronic imbalance may promote low-grade inflammation, which is linked to conditions like cardiovascular disease, autoimmune disorders, and metabolic syndrome.

2. Prone to Oxidation and Lipid Peroxidation:
Seed oils are highly unstable due to their polyunsaturated structure, meaning they easily oxidize when exposed to heat, light, and air.
When consumed, oxidized seed oils can lead to lipid peroxidation, which damages cell membranes, proteins, and DNA.
Oxidized LDL (low-density lipoprotein) is a significant contributor to atherosclerosis and cardiovascular disease.

3. Metabolic Disruption and Mitochondrial Dysfunction:

Linoleic acid (LA) is stored in body fat over time due to its slow turnover rate. Studies suggest excessive LA may impair mitochondrial function, leading to reduced ATP production and increased reactive oxygen species (ROS) generation.
This is particularly relevant in metabolic disorders like insulin resistance, obesity, and type 2 diabetes, where mitochondrial dysfunction plays a key role.
Rodent studies show that diets high in seed oils lead to obesity even when calories are controlled, suggesting a metabolic effect beyond caloric balance.

4. Endocannabinoid System Activation and Hunger Dysregulation:
Linoleic acid is a precursor to endocannabinoids, which are involved in appetite regulation.
Some research suggests that high-LA diets may overstimulate the endocannabinoid system, leading to increased hunger and fat storage.

5. Seed Oils and Cardiovascular Disease – Conflicting Evidence:
Proponents of seed oils argue that replacing saturated fats with polyunsaturated fats (PUFAs) reduces LDL cholesterol, which is associated with a lower risk of heart disease. However, while LDL lowering is observed, this does not necessarily translate to reduced cardiovascular events. Some studies indicate that replacing saturated fats with seed oils may increase all-cause mortality, possibly due to oxidative stress and inflammation.


Is There No Evidence Against Seed Oils?
Some researchers, particularly those aligned with mainstream nutrition (such as the American Heart Association), claim seed oils are harmless or even beneficial. However, much of their stance is based on epidemiological studies, which do not establish causation.

In contrast, many biochemical and mechanistic studies, animal experiments, and historical dietary patterns suggest that excessive seed oil consumption is a modern dietary anomaly and may contribute to chronic disease.

Moderate consumption of natural, unprocessed fats (such as animal fats, butter, coconut oil, olive oil, and macadamia oil) is preferable to highly refined seed oils.

The excessive consumption of linoleic acid from seed oils appears problematic, particularly when combined with a high-carb, high-processed-food diet.

Many "pro-seed oil" studies focus solely on LDL cholesterol and ignore oxidative stress, mitochondrial dysfunction, and inflammation.
While I wouldn't say that small amounts of seed oils are immediately toxic, a high-linoleic-acid diet is not evolutionarily consistent with human health.

Would you agree that the burden of proof should be on those claiming that these oils are safe, given their relatively recent introduction into the human die?

For instance, some of her work, particularly in areas like personalized nutrition and dietary interventions, has received support from companies such as ZOE Ltd, a personalized nutrition company co-founded by Tim Spector (also a researcher at King’s College). Key points to note:
1. **Disclosures in Publications**: Her academic papers often include funding disclosures. For example, studies like the PREDICT trials have listed support from multiple entities, including industry partners. These disclosures are typically noted in the conflict of interest sections of her publications.
2. **Institutional Partnerships**: King’s College London occasionally partners with industry for research. Dr. Berry’s involvement in such projects (e.g., with ZOE) highlights collaborative ties, though these are usually institutional rather than personal financial relationships.
3. **Advisory Roles**: She has participated in industry-sponsored conferences or advisory boards, which sometimes involve honoraria or travel reimbursements. These engagements are generally disclosed in her academic work or professional profiles.

**Conclusion**: Dr. Berry’s research has involved industry collaboration and funding, primarily through institutional partnerships and disclosed grants. comment_text:
From Steven's independent fact checking:

Research suggests that oils rich in unsaturated fats, such as olive (120-123) and canola oil (124-126), are generally preferred over saturated fats for cardiovascular health (127). A meta-analysis that included 54 trials found that safflower and rapeseed oils were most effective in reducing LDL cholesterol compared to butter (128). However, they may not significantly affect cholesterol levels when added to an average diet without other dietary modifications. An animal study comparing safflower to fish oil and control diets found that the safflower oil-fed rats were insulin resistant and showed reduced insulin-stimulated glucose disposal, resulting in increased triglyceride content in intramuscular muscle (129). Additionally, while medium-chain fatty acids appear not to affect serum cholesterol levels, lauric and myristic acids found in coconut and palm kernel oils can increase blood cholesterol (130). It is important to consider that there is a paucity of clinical trials analysing the effects of seed oils in humans, with most studies being in vitro or animal studies.

comment_text: This lady obviously hasn't done her research. Omega-6 PUFAs, are abundant in seed oils. A study published in Prostaglandins, Leukotrienes, and Essential Fatty Acids (2009) highlighted that an imbalance between omega-6 and omega-3 fatty acids in the modern diet may promote inflammatory processes. Omega-3 fatty acids, which are more prevalent in foods like fish and flaxseeds, are considered anti-inflammatory. A landmark study, the Sydney Diet Heart Study (1966), looked at the effects of replacing saturated fat with linoleic acid (a major omega-6 fatty acid in seed oils). The study found an increase in mortality from heart disease in the group consuming more seed oils, raising concerns about the safety of such fats. A study published in The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition (2009) pointed out that unrefined oils may have more health benefits compared to their refined counterparts, although further research is still needed. The Alpha Omega Trial (2010) found that omega-3 fatty acids had beneficial effects on cardiovascular health, but polyunsaturated fats (from seed oils) did not show clear evidence of reducing heart disease risk in the long run, especially when considering the balance of omega-3 to omega-6 fatty acids in the diet. The Minnesota Coronary Experiment is a pivotal study often cited in the discussion about seed oils and their potential health effects, especially in relation to heart disease. It’s one of the most significant trials to examine the impact of replacing saturated fats with polyunsaturated fats (specifically from vegetable oils, including seed oils) on cardiovascular health. Overall conclusion of the trial: The Minnesota Coronary Experiment found that substituting polyunsaturated fats (like those from seed oils) for saturated fats did not reduce, and possibly even increased, the risk of heart disease. The results were contrary to the widespread belief at the time that lowering cholesterol would automatically reduce heart disease risk.

comment_text:
I was surprised that she was extremely brief about sugar, carbs, nothing about insulin resistance, ketosis. Also, I've seen studies on other channels which showed that high level of LDL (bad cholesterol) are not correlated with mortality from cardio vascular deceases. And, regarding saturated fat,  I've seen quite a few experts (here on youtube) with opposite view. For example per Ben Bikman, it is not fat alone, but its consumption along with carbs that contributes to its negative impact on blood vessels. In other words if you are on keto, then high fat, even saturated, is good.
Last but not least, I'm just puzzled when people use this phrase: "diets don't work". What is a diet and what is not? If it is known that high sugar and high processed food consumption is bad, then wouldn't it be a diet if I reduce or eliminate those foods? Any particular food regiment, unless you just swallow anything you see and any time you want, is a diet of some sort. So I think it is much more useful to distinguish the diets which are based on science and studies, vs. those that have no supporting data.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text: From reading the comments, it's scary how people take each guest scientist's advice as gospel. They have each done specialist research in different fields and give recommendations through their lens. As a scientist myself, I understand how research can sometimes oppose another's research... ultimately, you as a consumer of all the info, need to find an equilibrium point for what you want to follow. The guest scientists are also humans - who have experienced life differently, and so their research is communicated through their lens as individuals. Personally, I loved this episode because for one of the first times, a guest has said that strict diets are not sustainable, especially through certain difficult periods in life. If a ketogenic diet works for you.... great! Maybe for me, it doesn't work. Maybe intermittent fasting does not work well with my IBS. We all have very different variables to consider. We don't need to villify any scientist individual or rage against the food industry. Just take all the info in and use what suits your individual needs!

	“Excessive consumption of omega-6 fatty acids, primarily from industrial seed oils, can contribute to a pro-inflammatory state when not balanced with omega-3 fatty acids.”
(Simopoulos, A.P., 2002)
	2.	Oxidation and Health Risks:
	•	Research in The Journal of Nutritional Biochemistry highlights:
	“Heating polyunsaturated fats, such as those in vegetable oils, leads to oxidation and the formation of harmful aldehydes, which have been linked to oxidative stress and chronic diseases.”
(Guedes et al., 2017)
	3.	Heart Health and Seed Oils:
	•	However, a review in Circulation suggests:
	“Replacing saturated fats with polyunsaturated fats, including seed oils, has been associated with a lower risk of coronary heart disease.”
(Mozaffarian & Clarke, 2009)
	4.	Industrial Processing Concerns:
	•	A study in Lipids in Health and Disease warns:
	“The refining process of vegetable oils often leads to the formation of trans fats and other toxic byproducts that may pose health risks.”
(Ghosh et al., 2020)

Takeaway:
	•	Seed oils can be a source of essential fatty acids but may promote inflammation if consumed in excess and are prone to oxidation when heated.
	•	Balancing omega-6 with omega-3 intake and choosing less refined oils can help mitigate risks.
	•	Some studies suggest seed oils may support heart health, but the benefits depend on overall dietary patterns.

This person is paid to speak in favour of seed oil … so bad!!!!

comment_text:
"There is absolutely no evidence that seed oils are unhealthy." This is a blanket statement that normally would demand at least some pushback from the interviewer. He gives none. Steven has had other guests who have touched on this topic. He could have at least raised the point that these seem to be legit people who say otherwise, and ask her if there might be something she is overlooking? 

Instead, he asks, "Is this just one of those things that snowballs?" Queuing her up to unhesitatingly say yes. But this is uninformed. I happen to know that is not true. I've been writing and speaking on this since 2002. It's one of those overnight sensations that's been decades in the making. 

 When she speaks about the meta-analysis of 42 studies around 1:10, she makes a blatant lie. She says all the randomized control trials come out the same way, in favor of her thesis that seed oils are healthy.  She says it several times so it's not just a mistake. She does not ever specify exactly which study she is citing but I would like to know. 

I have never seen a meta-analysis where all the results on this came out the same way. They're mixed. And the sneaky thing is they can exclude studies from their analysis that don't align with their belief system. This is done so often there are book chapters about it. So the results come out mixed even with these sneaky tricks. 

https://training.cochrane.org/handbook/current/chapter-13#:~:text=Risk%20of%20bias%20in%20a,considered%20unfavourable%20by%20the%20investigators).

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
The human body’s response to nutrients like saturated or unsaturated fats is profoundly shaped by individual genetic and metabolic uniqueness—factors such as variations in the **APOE, FADS1**, and **PPARG genes**, which influence fat absorption, inflammation, and cholesterol metabolism. Conventional nutrition studies, which pool data from genetically diverse groups, inherently obscure these critical differences. For example, a person with the **APOE ε4 allele** may face elevated cardiovascular risks on a high-saturated-fat diet, while someone with a **PPARG Ala12 variant** might thrive on the same diet. Similarly, those with **FADS1 "slow converter" genotypes** could suffer oxidative stress from seed oils but tolerate saturated fats. Yet, most studies ignore these nuances, averaging results across populations and yielding misleading "one-size-fits-all" conclusions. This approach is akin to prescribing the same shoe size to everyone—it works for some, harms others, and fits few perfectly.  

The truth is, **no single food or nutrient is universally "toxic" or "healthy."** For some, saturated fats (e.g., ghee, tallow) stabilize metabolism and reduce inflammation; for others, unsaturated fats (e.g., olive oil, nuts) are protective. A subset may even require strict limits on both, depending on genetic bottlenecks like impaired lipid clearance (*LPL gene*) or fatty liver predisposition (*PEMT gene*). Without analyzing an individual’s DNA, microbiome, and metabolic biomarkers (e.g., LDL particle size, triglyceride levels), broad dietary advice risks being irrelevant or harmful. Emerging fields like **nutrigenomics** and **precision nutrition** are challenging old paradigms, proving that personalized strategies—informed by genetic testing, continuous glucose monitors, and blood lipid tracking—are the future. Until science prioritizes individual profiling over population averages, the most reliable approach is self-experimentation: track how *your* body responds to fats, refine your diet accordingly, and view mainstream guidelines as loose frameworks, not gospel. @TheDiaryOfACEO ‼️we need nutrigenomics podcast ‼️

comment_text:
She mentions at minute 12:45 that she believes the "food industry ultimately wants to produce food that is safe but also healthy for us." While the industry has always been driven by the goal of selling, its approach is now evolving due to increasing awareness about the health impacts of ultra-processed food. Documentaries have shown how companies repeatedly tested their products with focus groups and control studies to make them not just palatable, but addictive—ensuring maximum sales. Perhaps, 50 years ago they didn't know the impact their products would have on people's health. 

Now, with more people demanding healthier options and greater awareness fueled by the internet and YouTubers like you, the industry is adapting. They want to sell healthier food, but only because customer demand leaves them no choice. Even so, their ultimate priority remains sales, so their focus will still be on making products as tasty and addictive as possible while appearing healthier (or being so) to make sure the customer is happy and keeps buying. 

I’m not sure what the solution is, but industries will always prioritize profits. The moral of the story is that either we regulate, monitor, and rely on public organizations and scientists to ensure that products are truly safe and healthy, or we risk being unable to trust the industry's claims.

comment_text:
Seed oils can be good in small amounts, but the American diet tends to be high in them, which can lead to inflammation. 
Explanation
Omega-6s
Seed oils are high in omega-6 fatty acids, which can help protect against heart disease and improve cholesterol levels. However, too many omega-6s can lead to inflammation, which can contribute to disease. 
Refining
Seed oils are often refined to make them more stable for cooking. This process can remove beneficial compounds and create unhealthy trans-fats. 
Foods that contain seed oils
Many foods that contain seed oils, like french fries and packaged snacks, are also high in refined carbohydrates, sugar, and sodium. 
Examples of seed oils 
Canola oil, Corn oil, Cottonseed oil, Grapeseed oil, Peanut oil, Rice bran oil, Safflower oil, Soybean oil, and Sunflower oil.
Alternatives to seed oils Avocado oil, Extra virgin olive oil, Coconut oil, and Beef tallow.

comment_text:
How lucky is it to go to bed hungry? Many years ago, I was a fitness addict who ran marathons. When running marathons, it’s important not to weigh too much. This led me to eat too little and the wrong kinds of food. Over time, my body began to protest, and I developed poor sleep, among other issues. I could wake up after 8 hours of sleep and feel completely exhausted. At the same time, I also developed knee and back problems, which forced me to stop all training. Despite stopping, my sleep was still poor. I would wake up after 8 hours feeling exhausted, except on Monday mornings.

I started wondering why I felt tired on Tuesday mornings but not on Mondays. I realized that on Sunday evenings, after work, I would eat a larger meal before going to bed. At the time, I was a student and drove a taxi all weekend. Normally, my last meal was around 7 PM. I then began eating a small, light meal every evening at 11 PM. This allowed me to sleep 7 hours and feel refreshed. I’ve been doing this for the last 35 years.

I usually sleep around 6–7 hours every night. After breakfast—a slice of bread with egg and pickled herring—I do strength training 5 days a week. During the day, I typically eat chicken salad and crispbread.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
🚨For deeper nuance on seed oils, please read this comment (from a PhD Scientist in Metabolism, Oxford and Harvard Medical School) - Based on the emails and direct messages I’ve received since this episode was released I think there are some matters of confusion that deserve clarification regarding “seed oils” and omega-6 and 3 fats. First, it’s important not to equate “seed oils,” which is a rather fluffy term, with omega-6 fats. Needless to say, french fry oil and a walnut are not the same. I agree with the guest on the whole that Omega-6 fear mongering is overblown. However, it’s incorrect to suggest there are no issues with respect to omega-6 or “seed oil” consumption. The discussion starting at ~1:02:00 is overly dismissive, in my opinion and rather condescending. First there are data suggesting an Omega-6/3 imbalance can directly cause inflammation & metabolic dysfunction. Such studies are actually best done in genetically modified mice since the key omega-6 and 3 are essential nutrients that can’t be synthesized by the body; thus, you need to change other components of the diet to manipulate ratios in humans. Also - and CRITICALLY - it’s practically not possible to conduct the sorts of long-term RCTs one would need to detect a clinically meaningful difference that may result as a function of changing tissue/organ ratios of omega-6/3 ratios in humans. Such trials would need to last many months or even years. Thus, with respect to what’s considered “top tier evidence” there is a deficiency of data. That’s true. However, neither it’s a matter of “absence of (long-term RCT) is not absence of evidence (or harm.” If you’d like more thoughts on seed oils, please see this video: https://youtu.be/0eMguvxWWf4. I think anyone who takes the time to watch will agree there is more nuance in this topic than the podcast discussion reviews. 

I’d be more than happy to dialogue long-form with the host or guest. I’ve had a listen to most of the episode and agree with many comments from the guest, but would also offer a different perspective on some matters, like the causative role (or lack thereof) of calories in obesity and the legitimacy of the “in moderation” approach.

@@mrcheese3981 fair questions! I like your thinking. They should definitely provide some more information about the fact check there. 

People doing their own research can have big flaws because understanding the studies and the context takes some experience. As Sarah points out there’s different types of evidence that have more weight. A randomised control trial with hundreds or thousands of people is way more compelling than a single test tube or a mouse for instance. 

Then there’s questions of sample sizes, methodologies, weight of evidence etc etc. it’s not enough to google a paper and read it and decide that that’s the one. 

So some degree of education in research and in the area specifically is needed to properly assess the evidence. The average person on the street may not know how to weigh these up effectively.

comment_text: The "tightly controlled studies" on seed oils referenced by Dr. Berry would have to extend 3-5 years in order to account for the effects of omega 6 fatty acids in cell membrane composition, which dietary omega 6 alters only over such extended periods. Such studies are never done, because it is not feasible to feed controlled diets to test subjects for more than one or two months. Also, Chris Knobbe, the leading seed oil skeptic, is careful not to offer his hypotheses with certainty, as Dr. Berry claims. Given the infeasibility of tightly controlled studies of long term effects, he simply points out correlation in large population models, and he does take pains to control for  the multiple other factors (carbohydrate consumption, exercise levels, sugar, etc.) that, as he and Dr. Berry acknowledge, have also changed over the time periods in question.

comment_text:
Hi Steve, in general i always like your podcasts. Sometimes because it helps, sometimes to get me out of my comfort zone in the search of "nutricien truth" that works for me. I am most comfortable in my keto (lifestyle, not diet) modus, however currently still in a big repair effort, and will therefor admit that her speach is more difficult to listen to because I'm steering on healthy fats and proteines. I switch between back and forth between 2 meals a day and OMAD. I did not like her presentation for too many reasons. For me i notice that with animal fats my days and nights are SO much better, and i have had too many experts come with scientific evidence stating the unhealty production process of seed oils (excluding olive oil, as long as its unadulterated). But ok, i was willing to listen to the other side. But then she pulls the move "i could explain for an hour the pathway but your listeners are not interested", that is such a bad choice. If you have something radical to say, that you will have to do better lady! Her simple statements about dairy are also dangerous. I am so glad i have learned about A1 vs A2 milk, and also that i learned to recognize that cheese gives me much more danger of "urge". 

I dont mind that she is connected to ZOE and that she gets paid for almond nutricienal research, but the fact that is both, and that she speaks of opposites in terms of oils, dairy and saturated fat, without SHOWING her evidence, that made me decide not to finish the podcast.

Ps: it helps to let viewers realize that her presentation is for people without health issues. Because i am trying to stay away from people that try to get me back to "just have your chocolate" and "just go to the pub at night" while i am so busy defeating big pharma with good nutricien, excersize and sleep. Oh, i liked her story on the perfect storm (diet influencing sleep influencing morning nutricien choices) a lot.

I do like these podcasts as well made, but they are always around 5 years behind with politics (comparing to Rogan, Modern Wisdom etc) 10 years behind with fasting fashions, way behind and basic with weight training and nutrition, and always left wondering why I’m using my time as there’s nothing new to learn ever, I guess it’s for the entertainment.

comment_text:
1:01:52 Some important details about saturated vs polyunsaturated fatty acids: The high amounts, typically 20:1 ratio, of Omega-6 vs Omega-3 polyunsaturated fats, in a modern highly processed food diet is what makes the them pro-inflammatory and toxic. Here's some details. 



How much does it take to create transfats in omega-6 rich seed oils through cooking?

Creating trans fats in omega-6 rich seed oils through cooking primarily involves a process called partial hydrogenation, but this is not typically what happens during regular cooking. Here's a breakdown:


Partial Hydrogenation: This is an industrial process where hydrogen is added to liquid vegetable oils to make them more solid, increase shelf life, and improve flavor stability. This process can produce trans fats. However, this isn't something that occurs in home cooking.

Cooking Temperatures: 

Frying: When oils like soybean, corn, or sunflower oil (rich in omega-6) are heated to high temperatures (above their smoke points), they can undergo chemical changes. However, the production of trans fats at home cooking temperatures is relatively minimal. 

Smoke Point: Most seed oils have smoke points around 400°F (204°C) to 450°F (232°C). If you exceed these temperatures, you risk not only creating trans fats but also reducing the nutritional quality of the oil through oxidation and degradation.


Amount of Trans Fats Created: 

The amount of trans fats created during regular cooking is very small. Studies suggest that heating oils to their smoke point might increase trans fat content, but typically, this increase is only a few percent of the total fat content. For instance, one study showed an increase from negligible amounts to around 1-3% trans fat when oils were heated to high temperatures.

Frequency and Duration: The longer and more frequently an oil is heated, the more trans fats might be produced. However, this still doesn't compare to the levels found in industrially partially hydrogenated oils.


In Summary: 

Home Cooking: You'd need to heat oils significantly above their smoke points repeatedly to produce a noticeable amount of trans fats, which isn't common in everyday cooking. 

Industrial Processes: The significant production of trans fats occurs through industrial hydrogenation, not through cooking at home.


If you're concerned about trans fat intake, focus more on avoiding foods known to contain partially hydrogenated oils rather than worrying about trans fats formed during cooking. However, for health, it's still good practice not to overheat oils, as this can lead to other health concerns like increased levels of harmful compounds.

Post

Is there any research proving that the high ratio of omega-6 fats to Omega-3 in a modern diet creates inflammation?

Yes, there is substantial research exploring the relationship between the high ratio of omega-6 (n-6) to omega-3 (n-3) fatty acids in modern diets and inflammation. Here's a summary of key findings:


Research Overview:

Historical Dietary Ratios:
Historically, human diets had a balance closer to 1:1 or 4:1 of n-6 to n-3 fatty acids. Modern Western diets, however, often have ratios ranging from 15:1 to 20:1 or even higher, largely due to the increased consumption of vegetable oils high in n-6 fats like soybean, corn, and sunflower oils.

Mechanism of Inflammation:

Omega-6 fatty acids, particularly arachidonic acid, can be metabolized into pro-inflammatory eicosanoids like prostaglandins, leukotrienes, and thromboxanes. Omega-3 fatty acids, like EPA and DHA, compete with omega-6 for the same enzyme pathways but produce less inflammatory or even anti-inflammatory eicosanoids.

A high n-6/n-3 ratio can shift this balance towards more inflammation because there's less competition from omega-3s to mitigate the inflammatory response.

Key Studies:

Simopoulos AP (2002) in "The importance of the ratio of omega-6/omega-3 essential fatty acids" discusses how this imbalance may contribute to the pathogenesis of many diseases, including cardiovascular diseases, cancer, and inflammatory and autoimmune diseases.

Calder PC (2010) in "n-3 Polyunsaturated fatty acids, inflammation, and inflammatory diseases" reviews how increasing omega-3 intake can reduce inflammation, suggesting a link between dietary fats and inflammatory states.

Patterson E et al. (2012) found in "Health implications of high dietary omega-6 polyunsaturated Fatty acids" that the high n-6/n-3 ratio could be linked to increased cardiovascular risk markers and inflammation.

Clinical Evidence:

Several clinical trials have shown that reducing the n-6/n-3 ratio through dietary changes or supplementation can decrease markers of inflammation like C-reactive protein (CRP), interleukin-6 (IL-6), and tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-α).

A meta-analysis by Rangel-Huerta et al. (2012) showed that omega-3 supplementation could reduce inflammation markers in healthy adults.

Caveats:

Not all omega-6 fats are pro-inflammatory; linoleic acid, for example, needs to be converted to arachidonic acid to promote inflammation, and this conversion is not always efficient or consistent across individuals.

The context of the diet, including the presence of antioxidants, other nutrients, and the overall dietary pattern, also influences the inflammatory effects of fatty acids.


Conclusion:

While there are individual differences in metabolism and response, the general consensus in the scientific community is that a high omega-6 to omega-3 ratio can contribute to an inflammatory state, which might predispose individuals to chronic diseases. However, this is part of a broader dietary and lifestyle context. Therefore, dietary adjustments towards balancing these fatty acids are often recommended for health benefits, particularly in reducing chronic inflammation.

comment_text:
She's an expert but have no problems with seed oils?

1. High in Omega-6 Fatty Acids

    Many seed oils (e.g., soybean oil, corn oil, sunflower oil) are rich in omega-6 fatty acids, a type of polyunsaturated fat. While omega-6 is essential for the body, an imbalance between omega-6 and omega-3 fatty acids can promote chronic inflammation. Modern diets often contain a high omega-6 to omega-3 ratio, which has been linked to health issues like cardiovascular disease and metabolic disorders.

2. Highly Processed

    Most seed oils undergo extensive industrial processing, often involving high heat and chemicals like hexane to extract the oil. This process can degrade nutrients and produce harmful compounds, such as trans fats, even in small amounts.

3. Oxidation and Free Radicals

    Seed oils are sensitive to heat, light, and air due to their high polyunsaturated fat content. When exposed to these elements during cooking or storage, they can oxidize, producing free radicals and other harmful byproducts. These compounds can contribute to oxidative stress, which is linked to aging, inflammation, and chronic diseases.

4. Potential Contaminants

    The manufacturing process can introduce impurities or residues from solvents and other chemicals. Additionally, some seed oils may be extracted from genetically modified crops, raising concerns for those who avoid GMOs.

5. Nutritional Profile

    Seed oils often lack the beneficial nutrients found in minimally processed oils like extra virgin olive oil or unrefined coconut oil. For example, olive oil contains antioxidants and monounsaturated fats, which are considered heart-healthy, while seed oils typically do not.

Healthier Alternatives:

If you're concerned about seed oils, consider using:

    Extra virgin olive oil: Rich in monounsaturated fats and antioxidants.
    Coconut oil: Stable at high heat and minimally processed.
    Avocado oil: High smoke point and nutrient-rich.
    Butter or ghee: Natural animal fats that are stable for cooking.

comment_text:
@@sheering09 This comment misunderstands the fundamental chemistry involved. The health concerns with these oils aren't primarily about processing methods or whether they're organic - it's about the inherent chemical properties of their fatty acids.

Even cold-pressed, organic oils containing unstable polyunsaturated fats will:

Begin oxidizing at relatively low temperatures (40-50°C for omega-3)
Form harmful compounds like hydroperoxides, aldehydes, and acrolein when heated
Trigger chain reactions leading to cellular damage
Create toxic byproducts that can harm cell membranes and DNA

This is basic chemistry - the molecules will behave the same way regardless of how they were extracted or whether the plants were grown organically. It's like saying an organic match burns more safely than a regular match - the chemical reaction remains the same.

Your bread analogy isn't quite applicable here since we're dealing with different issues. While organic farming practices can affect nutrient content and chemical residues, they don't change how unstable fatty acids react to heat or oxygen. The chemistry of oxidation will occur whether the oil is organic, cold-pressed, or conventional.

The scientific evidence shows cellular damage from these oxidized oils occurs regardless of their production method. It's the fundamental nature of the fatty acids themselves that creates these problems when heated or exposed to oxygen over time.

She's actually not wrong, VERY SPECIFIC seeds can be pressed for oil. They've done it in India with safflower seeds for a long time apparently.

HOWEVER, the industry takes seeds and oils that were never meant for consumption and runs them through chemical processes to remove certain toxins (ie. Cottonseeds to Crisco, soybeans to soybean oil, etc.) And to add insult to injury seeds that may be pressed naturally have chemicals added to them to increase the yield and add shelf life.

I would recommend avoiding seed oils as much as possible unless you thoroughly do your research or decide to try and do it yourself.

Edit: Just over halfway through the video. There was no reason to go after beef tallow like that. Also comparing US vs. UK is completely unfair because the UK has better health practices when applied to food.

She is an industry plant :
She works for the BRITISH NUTRITION FOUNDATION - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Nutrition_Foundation
The British Nutrition Foundation is a British lobby group mainly funded by the food industry. It has been widely criticised for conflicts of interest, and for downplaying them. It presents itself to journalists, the public, and the government as an independent, impartial, disinterested, and scientifically rigorous; its industry funders also promote this image.

The BNF has opposed many public-health interventions that might harm food-industry profits, often using tobacco-industry techniques, such as creating unwarranted doubt and uncertainty around the scientific evidence.
In 2023, the BNF had an income of £1.5million, with an expenditure of £1.6million. £0.113million were spent on fundraising.

The British Nutrition Foundation (BNF) receives funding from a wide range of food and drink companies, including major players like *Coca-Cola, Nestlé, Mondelēz, PepsiCo, Mars, Danone, Kerry, and Cargill*. This funding structure has raised concerns about potential conflicts of interest, particularly given the BNF's role in shaping nutrition policy and its relationship with the food industry, according to a LinkedIn post. The BNF has been described as a "bridge between government, science, industry, and education" but critics argue that its funding model compromises its impartiality and ability to act independently, according to a LinkedIn post. The foundation's acceptance of funding from companies whose products are linked to diet-related diseases has been highlighted as a particular area of concern.

comment_text:
I propose you to invite the great Nina Teicholz for the counterarguments.

In short, her (Sarah Berrys) argument is: before, seed oils were bad because of the way we processed them at that time, creating trans fat. Now, we create them differently. And we need to trust experts that now that process is better. I don't buy it, especially because she seems to put herself on the 'researcher high-ground', as if the idea of seed oil being bad is a social media thing (while she can't deny it was, at least in the past, true). 

I trust Nina Teicholz better, who claims (in her classic 'The Big Fat Surprize') that the new processes for creating seed oil is as bad as before, but that there are too few studies they did to check whether they are healthy or not. Research is heavily sponsored by the industry, resulting in limited focus studies giving the opportunity to experts to say that if you know the hard studies, this and that is not unhealthy.

A copious amount of horrific child abuse and neglect, growing up becoming a strong man who's had the rug pulled from underneath me by family who I thought I could help. When I matured enough to set healthy boundaries my family quit speaking to me. My son's mother has been cheating on me for 10 years straight. I guess I held on because I never really had a family and I was scared to lose what I had. Another part of me just didn't want my son to grow up in a broken home as I did.  I built a successful business. A more powerful company in the area in an attempt to get me to come work for them destroyed mine. I've dreamed of the stars and I touched them. Just before I got my arms around them; time and time again the world has pulled me down. The hell in my head hasn't left. My mindset has. I've been a good man,  good father set a way better spouse than I should have been.  I am a humble person by nature but I'm also very fierce and strong-willed. Never in my life have I ever let another man stand next to me and out work me. I'm 37 years old now. When I found out that my spouse is cheating on me again, I broke. Being hooked up to machines fighting for my life and then going to the psych ward was what it took to remove me from the hell that was my life. I was out of reach of all of my trauma for just 30 days locked in a co-ed Ward. While I was there I got to be me again for the first time in 13 years. Had I not did the horrible things I did to harm myself, I would have died anyways because I hadn't eaten in 6 months anything more than a meal every day or two. I was down to 125 lb.  I was already dying. When I hit that bottle of pills I went to my shed but didn't make it in my neighbor found me. I was convulsing. I feel like God snatched me by the scruff of my shirt it shook me out of the situation I was in because I deserve better. I'm ashamed of myself for not respecting myself more. video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
I found this episode difficult to finish. It took me 2 days. I felt like I was listening to my doctor telling me that my experience could not have happened, again. I continued to listen because I don’t want to fall prey to confirmation bias. I want to understand.

The doctor is pleasant, polite, committed, educated, humble, caring, old enough to have the respect of age and young enough to be extremely attractive. She is convincing and easy to watch — until you listen closely to what she’s saying. Her belief in standard theories of nutrition is… unsettling.

She is genuine. She believes, as do many doctors, standard nutritional advice. However, when I followed this standard advice, I continued to have health issues. These only resolved when I tried some of methods that she refers to as “nutribullocks.” And I am not alone. I am joined my numerous doctors and researchers that have followed, the standard advice, and still developed the health issues that following that advice was supposed to prevent.

Simply put, it’s bad science to decide to ignore anecdotal evidence or case studies. These events happened. If your theory fails to address these exceptions, it cannot be accepted as fact. If statistical or observational analysis haven’t found an issues with your theory — and issues still exist — you don’t have an answer. Absence of evidence cannot provide evidence of absence.

It is either naive or ignorant to suggest that there is no influence from a funding body, even though the funding body is not involved in the actual research. After all, no matter what grant request you write, the funder gets to choose what they will fund or will not fund. That choice leaves many of us in the dark.

As businesses food corporations will approve what they feel is safe for them to approve. Will they continue to fund a researcher that has proven their products to be unsafe? Will they pull or change a ingredients for more expensive options unless they are forced to?

Look at it this way. It’s like a detective [a scientist] being directed where to look [with funding approval] for a body [a toxic effect] by a suspect [food or pharmaceutical corporation].

People are trying to be healthier. The smoking gun is the continuing increases in chronic illnesses that are plaguing us at younger and younger ages under the status quo.

video_title: The Nutritional Scientist: Do Not Eat After 9pm! Link Between Chewing & Belly Fat!
comment_text:
It’s good to bring in people like this occasionally to see multiple sides of how people view things. Don’t listen to unsubscribing threats from viewers who disagree with this woman or who would want to see you take her apart with critical questions. 

This woman was on the offensive against the internet and of course that back fires. Staying neutral and letting her talk was just fine. You didn’t ’side’ with ‘the internet’ and played it neutral. That gives her the chance to state her opinion even if most of your viewers hate it. 

Viewers should be able to think a little themselves if they decide to trust this woman. If you are too critical on her view it’s just ‘buying’ your viewers who like their point of view enforced. 

I did not agree with or like this woman. But exactly that’s why I say thank you for letting her talk. Keep up the good work!

(After many episodes some times you playing dumb on a term/topic can be a little hard to watch :p)
